'''Enid Charles''' (29 December 1894 – 26 March 1972) was a [[socialist]], [[feminist]] and [[statistician]] who was a pioneer in the fields of [[demography]] and [[population statistics]].

She was born '''Dorothy Enid Charles''' in [[Denbigh]], [[Wales]]. She obtained a [[bachelor's degree]] in [[mathematics]], [[economics]] and [[statistics]] at [[Newnham College]], [[Cambridge University]] and a Ph.D. in [[physiology]] from the [[University of Cape Town]], [[South Africa]].<ref name=SW>{{citation | year = 2005 | author = Sylvia Wargon | title = Legacy of Enid Charles, 1894–1972 | journal = Canadian Studies in Population | volume = 32 | pages = 137–153 | url = http://www.canpopsoc.org/journal/CSPv32n2p137.pdf}}</ref>

Charles met the [[conscientious objector]] [[Lancelot Hogben]] while at Cambridge; they married in 1918.<ref name=TimesObit>{{citation | title = Dr. Enid Charles | newspaper = [[The Times]] | date = April 3, 1972}}</ref> Out of a dozen or so socialist and feminist couples in Britain in the early 20th century, Charles was the only wife to keep her name.<ref>{{citation | author = Outram, Dorinda; Abir-Am, Pnina G. | title = Uneasy Careers and Intimate Lives: Women in Science, 1789–1979 | publisher = Rutgers University Press | location = New Brunswick, N.J | year = 1987 | isbn = 0-8135-1256-5}}</ref>  The couple who had two sons and two daughters,<ref name=www>{{cite book|title=Who Was Who, 1971-1980|year=1981|publisher=A and C Black|page=375|isbn=0-7136-2176-1}}Sketch on Lancelot Hogben.</ref> separated in 1953 and divorced in 1957.<ref name=odnb>{{cite book|title=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, Volume 27|year=2004|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=0-19-861377-6}}Article on Hogben by Robert Bud.</ref>

Charles worked on [[fertility rate]]s and [[nuptiality]] for the [[Statistics Canada|Dominion Bureau of Statistics]] in [[Canada]]. In 1934, Charles projected drastic decline in population of the [[United Kingdom]] should the fertility rates continue to fall. These results led her to speak out against the then commonly accepted principle of [[eugenics]].<ref>{{citation | year = 1996 | author = W.H.G. Armytage | title = The Social Context of Eugenic Thought | publisher = [[Galton Institute]] | url = http://www.galtoninstitute.org.uk/Newsletters/GINL9606/index.html}}</ref><ref>{{citation | year = 1993 | author = Pedersen, Susan | title = Family, Dependence, and the Origins of the Welfare State in Britain and France, 1914–1945 | publisher = Cambridge University Press | location = Cambridge, UK | pages = | isbn = 0-521-55834-4}}</ref> She subsequently worked as a Regional Adviser in Epidemiology and Health Statistics and as a Population Statistics Consultant for the [[World Health Organization]] in [[Singapore]] and [[New Delhi]].<ref name=SW/>

She died in [[Torquay]], [[England]], in 1972, aged 77.<ref name=TimesObit/>

